SIMPLE: prerogative
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prerogative
<hw>Pre*rog"a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧rogative</ets>, from L. <ets>praerogativa</ets>
precedence in voting, preference, privilege, fr.
<ets>praerogativus</ets> that is asked before others for his opinion,
that votes before or first, fr. <ets>praerogare</ets> to ask before
another; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>rogare</ets> to ask. See
<er>Rogation</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>An exclusive or peculiar privilege; prior and
indefeasible right; fundamental and essential possession; -- used
generally of an official and hereditary right which may be asserted
without question, and for the exercise of which there is no
responsibility or accountability as to the fact and the manner of its
exercise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The two faculties that are the <qex>prerogative</qex> of man --
the powers of abstraction and imagination.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An unconstitutional exercise of his <qex>prerogative</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Precedence; pre⟦eum⟧minence; first rank.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then give me leave to have <qex>prerogative</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The term came into general use in the conflicts between
the Crown and Parliaments of Great Britain, especially in the time of
the Stuarts.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Prerogative Court</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>a
court which formerly had authority in the matter of wills and
administrations, where the deceased left <xex>bona notabilia</xex>, or
effects of the value of five pounds, in two or more different
dioceses.</cd> <au>Blackstone.</au> -- <col><b>Prerogative
office</b></col>, <cd>the office in which wills proved in the
Prerogative Court were registered.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Privilege; right. See
<er>Privilege</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prerogatived</ent>⟦br⟧
